<font color="#FF0000">THOUGHTS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  1 20:50:53 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Others have judged us. We have judged ourselves. All judgements are the product of fact or fiction passing through the life experience filters in us all. Life experience filters include belief systems, action and reaction systems, and all the rest of those things that accumulate in us all over time.<br><br>
One positive thing about life experience filters is that they are always changing. The person or personality I am today is very different from that which I was 27 or so years ago. Speaking only for myself, I have a problem with some life experience filters that got stuck back in 'Nam. For example, the &quot;baby killer&quot; judgement of so long ago feels as real today as it did then, and I still get torn up about it if it grabs me and runs. Intellectually, I know it to be untrue. I did not deliberately kill babies. No decent soldier even thinks otherwise. Emotionally, however, it is an entirely different matter. The problem is putting that which I experience today into those stuck life filters, and trust it enough, to let the old stuff go and become bad memories instead of a time warp reality that tears me to pieces.<br><br>
Trust in what I now see and trust in what I now feel is the key. <br><br>
I admit I need to be led at times, and I need a beacon. It is funny, but the trauma processing group in which I now participate makes me both a beacon, torch bearer to some, while I gladly accept assistance from others to be led.<br><br>
The answers I seek are both inside me and within my friends. <br><br>
We trust. We trust completely. We *are* brothers of choice.<br><br>

<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


